body.p:
The common tags in the header are: @project @lang
@name.  In addition, the header may specify the target language
for @sense elements (@translang, which
defaults to en, English); describe the CBD version with
@cbd, and reference one or more configuration files for
the properties and relations mechanisms: @proplist
@relators.

The entry block is the first part of an entry. An entry begins with
@entry and ends with @end entry.  In
addition, the entry block may contain one or more @alias
tags which give alternate names for the entry.  If the
@entry is a compound, the entry block must also contain
one or more @parts elements.

There are also CBD Edit constructs that are associated with
@entry but use of these is presently restricted to
ePSD.

body.pre:
@entry e [speak] V/t
@allow b°e₇ = n°e
@bases b°e₂ (be₂); b°e₄; b°e₇; m°e; n°e

@entry ina [in] PRP
@form ip-pa-ni-šu₂ $ina $(pānišu)
@form ip-pa-ni-šu₂-nu $ina $(pānišunu)
@form ...
@sense PRP ina
@sense ...
@end entry

...

entry pānu [front] N
@form ip-pa-ni-šu₂ $(ina) $pānišu
@form ip-pa-ni-šu₂-nu $(ina) $pānišunu
@form ...
@sense N front
@end entry

ul.li:
NORM must be given explicitly; simply use the value of MORPH and
replace the ~ (tilde) component with the citation
form;

body.pre:
@entry šuš [cover] V/t
@bases suš₂; u°šu₂
@form   ušu₂ /u°šu₂ #~ $(ud) $šuš
@sense V/t to cover, to spread over
@end entry

@entry ud [sun] N
@bases ud; u·šu₂
@form   ušu₂  /u·šu₂ #~ $ud $(šuš)
@sense N sun
@end entry

dl.dd:
A text field which declares the known values for STEM in the
  @form lines for the @entry.  This is stored but no further action is
  presently taken with it.

body.pre:
@entry a [water] N
@sense N water
@sense .1 N water
@sense #1 N water
@sense #1 .1 N water
@sense #1 .1 [water] N water

@senses
@sense N water
@note This sense is dubious.
@end senses

+@sense N water
-@sense N water
@sense N water
> V/t to water
@sense N water
>> V/t to water

@project epsd2
@lang sux
@name epsd2/lang
@i18n fr

@entry ur [dog] N
@gwl %fr chien
@sense N dog
@sensel %fr chien
@disc I prefer cats.
@discl %fr Moi, je préfère les chats.
@note We expect a note here.
@notel %fr Ici on attend une note.
@end entry

body.p:
The @entry, @sense, and
@form tags may be followed by an exclamation mark, e.g.,
@form!, indicating higher lemmatizer priority.
